    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &amp;-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &amp;M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/55dde3d4ea5e6d9e321ca34ebfdd37268558e1aa" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.505ex; width:25.981ex; height:6.176ex;" alt="{\displaystyle M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &amp;-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &amp;M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}}"/></span>where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix. They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity". Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.<sup about="#mwt400" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-:4_60-3" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":":4"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-:4-60"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-:4-60" id="mwA-g"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwA-k"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA-o">[</span>58<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA-s">]</span></span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA-w">There are also mixed seq2seq models. For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.<sup about="#mwt401" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-gtrans_44-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"gtrans"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-gtrans-44" id="mwA-0"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwA-4"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA-8">[</span>42<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA_A">]</span></span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="27" id="mwA_E"><h2 id="Subsequent_work">Subsequent work</h2>
<section data-mw-section-id="28" id="mwA_I"><h3 id="Alternative_activation_functions">Alternative activation functions</h3>
<p id="mwA_M">The original transformer uses <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./ReLU" title="ReLU" class="mw-redirect" id="mwA_Q">ReLU</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Activation_function" title="Activation function" id="mwA_U">activation function</a>. Other activation functions were developed. The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Llama_(language_model)" title="Llama (language model)" id="mwA_Y">Llama series</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./PaLM" title="PaLM" id="mwA_c">PaLM</a> used SwiGLU;<sup about="#mwt404" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-:14_69-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":":14"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-:14-69"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-:14-69" id="mwA_g"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwA_k"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA_o">[</span>67<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA_s">]</span></span></a></sup> both GPT-1 and BERT<sup about="#mwt405" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-:03_42-4" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":":03"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-:03-42" id="mwA_w"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwA_0"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA_4">[</span>40<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwA_8">]</span></span></a></sup> used GELU.<sup about="#mwt408" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-70" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-70"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-70" id="mwBAA"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBAE"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBAI">[</span>68<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBAM">]</span></span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBAQ">Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gated_Linear_Unit" title="Gated Linear Unit" class="mw-redirect" id="mwBAU">Gated Linear Units</a> in the feedforward module.<sup about="#mwt409" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-:14_69-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":":14"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-:14-69" id="mwBAY"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBAc"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBAg">[</span>67<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBAk">]</span></span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="29" id="mwBAo"><h3 id="Alternative_normalizations">Alternative normalizations</h3>
<p id="mwBAs">The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm. One example is <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./RMSNorm" title="RMSNorm" class="mw-redirect" id="mwBAw">RMSNorm</a><sup about="#mwt412" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-71" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-71"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-71" id="mwBA0"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBA4"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBA8">[</span>69<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBBA">]</span></span></a></sup> which is used in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Llama_(language_model)" title="Llama (language model)" id="mwBBE">Llama series</a>. Other examples include ScaleNorm<sup about="#mwt415" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-:9_72-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":":9"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-:9-72"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-:9-72" id="mwBBI"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBBM"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBBQ">[</span>70<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBBU">]</span></span></a></sup> and FixNorm.<sup about="#mwt416" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-:9_72-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":":9"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-:9-72" id="mwBBY"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBBc"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBBg">[</span>70<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBBk">]</span></span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="30" id="mwBBo"><h3 id="Alternative_positional_encodings">Alternative positional encodings</h3>
<p id="mwBBs">Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.<sup about="#mwt419" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-73" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-73"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-73" id="mwBBw"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBB0"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBB4">[</span>71<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBB8">]</span></span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBCA">The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding,<sup about="#mwt422" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-74" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-74"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-74" id="mwBCE"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBCI"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBCM">[</span>72<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBCQ">]</span></span></a></sup> but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.<sup about="#mwt423" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-2017_Attention_Is_All_You_Need_1-11" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"2017_Attention_Is_All_You_Need"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-2017_Attention_Is_All_You_Need-1" id="mwBCU"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBCY"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBCc">[</span>1<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBCg">]</span></span></a></sup> Later,<sup about="#mwt426" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-75" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-75"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-75" id="mwBCk"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBCo"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBCs">[</span>73<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBCw">]</span></span></a></sup> found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.</p>

<section data-mw-section-id="31" id="mwBC0"><h4 id="RoPE">RoPE</h4>
<p id="mwBC4"><span class="anchor" id="Rotary_positional_embedding" about="#mwt427" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Anchor","href":"./Template:Anchor"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Rotary positional embedding"}},"i":0}}]}'></span>RoPE (rotary positional embedding),<sup about="#mwt430" class="mw-ref reference" id="cite_ref-76" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-76"}}'><a href="./Transformer_(deep_learning)#cite_note-76" id="mwBC8"><span class="mw-reflink-text" id="mwBDA"><span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBDE">[</span>74<span class="cite-bracket" id="mwBDI">]</span></span></a></sup> is best explained by considering a list of 2-dimensional vectors <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline" typeof="mw:Extension/math" about="#mwt431" data-mw='{"name":"math","attrs":{},"body":{"extsrc":"[(x^{(1)}_1, x^{(2)}_1), (x^{(1)}_2, x^{(2)}_2), (x^{(1)}_3, x^{(2)}_3), ...]"}}' id="mwBDM"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle [(x_{1}^{(1)},x_{1}^{(2)}),(x_{2}^{(1)},x_{2}^{(2)}),(x_{3}^{(1)},x_{3}^{(2)}),...]}">
